50|$|A {{kerosene}} heater, {{also known}} as a paraffin heater, is typically a portable, unvented, kerosene-fueled, space (i.e. convectional) heating device. In Japan and other countries, they are a primary source of <b>home</b> <b>heat.</b> In the United States and Australia, they are a supplemental heat or a source of emergency heat during a power outage. Most kerosene heaters produce between 3.3 and 6.8 kW (11000 to 23000 BTU per hour).|$|R
